NO. 274 E LOKA NAM (Beyond the Sea)

1. E loka nam mopogo kind 
Piny chandruokni kod gik mak ne; 
Nitie pinyno ma ok norum 
Ka ma pi wang' noywe duto.

E loka nam- e nam mogingore--
(E loka nam mogingore, mogingore) 
Awinjo duond-- Jawarna ka luonga-- 
(Awinjo duond jawarna ka luonga luonga)
Ndalo chiegni-- mawanawe chandruok--
(Ndalo chiegni ma wanawe chandruok chandruok) 
Mawanadag gi Ruoth manyaka chieng'

2. E loka nam e dho wadh kuwe 
Kama richo duto norum; 
Kama chandruok ok nobedie 
Tiende mool noyud yweyo.

3. Onge paro gik mokadho 
Chunya mool noyud teko; 
Pi wang'wa ok nochwer kendo 
Wenge mool none Jawar.

4. E loka nam kar kuwe gi mor 
Yesu luongo nyithinde te; 
E loka nam parruok norum 
Malaika wero wend ruak. 
.
.
.
BEYOND THE SEA
1. Beyond the sea-- that rolls between;
This world of care-- and things unseen;
There is a land -- of endless day;
Where all our tears-- are wip'd away.

Beyond the sea--- the restless tolling sea---
(Beyond the sea, beyond the sea)
I hear my lov'd --ones gently calling me---
(I hear my lov'd one calling, gently calling me)
I soon shall --- leave the troubles shores of time---;
(I soon shall leave the shores of time, the shores of time)
And dwell for aye--, in that celestial clime.
(And dwell for aye-- in that celestial clime).

2. Beyond the sea-- lies heav's fair shore;
Where all sin--- and earth are o'er;
Where care and toil-- have pass'd away;
Where weary feet-- no more shall stray.

3. No more shall beat-- the flood of years;
Across these forms-- so frail and worn;
No more shall roll -- the sea of tears;
Across these harts-- by anguish torn.

4. Beyond the sea-- there's rest and peace;
There Jesus bids- His child come home;
Beyond the sea-- the tempests cease;
There angels sing-- a welcome home.

- Frank H. Mashaw

